      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Pegasus Buchanan (1918-2006) was an American poet.  Born in Lansing, Michigan she graduated from Michigan State 
	  University and in 1950 moved to Pomona, California with her husband Barney Barnum, where she became involved with the literary 
	  and artistic life of the community.  She was the poetry editor of the Southern California publication 
	  <emph render="italic">L.A. Magazine</emph> for a number of years and received 
	  numerous awards, including the Pomona Valley Award for the promotion of children's literature, the Pomona Valley Library 
	  Award, and the College Arts Award.  The Pomona Valley Writers Club established the annual Pegasus Award in her name, 
	  which honors children for their poetry.</p>
	  <p>Her published collections include <emph render="italic">Chestnut Street</emph>, 
	  <emph render="italic">Kingsley Alley</emph> and <emph render="italic">Wilderness Trail</emph>, and her poems appeared in many 
	  national magazines, including <emph render="italic">The Saturday Evening Post</emph>, 
	  <emph render="italic">Good Housekeeping</emph>, <emph render="italic">The Ladies' Home Journal</emph>, <emph render="italic">McCall's</emph>, 
	  <emph render="italic">The Saturday Review</emph>, and <emph render="italic">The New York Times</emph>.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Pegasus Buchanan Papers</emph> consists of manuscripts and published material.</p>
		 <p><emph render="bold">Manuscripts</emph> include an unpublished book of children's verses entitled <emph render="italic">Talamo Tales</emph>, 
		 a galley proof of <emph render="italic">Kingsley Alley</emph>, and the original working copies of <emph render="italic">Chestnut Street</emph> and 
		 <emph render="italic">Kingsley Alley</emph>.</p>
		 <p><emph render="bold">Published material</emph> includes scrapbooks of newspaper and periodical clippings by Buchanan, and about her and her work.  
		 Also included is a complete run (14 issues) of <emph render="italic">L.A. Magazine</emph> and all of the poetry Buchanan collected during her term as 
		 poetry editor for that publication.  A copy of one of her books, <emph render="italic">Wilderness Trail</emph>, is also included.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
      <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
         <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
         <p>Other than the division into manuscript and published material, material is in no particular order.</p>
      </arrangement>
      
